(4/4) Just like asking dad for your fair share, the phrase "black lives matter" also has an implicit "too" at the end: it's saying that black lives should also matter. Responding to this by saying "all lives matter" is willfully ignoring the problem.

(3/4) The statement "I should get my fair share" had an implicit "too" at the end: "I should get my fair share, too, just like everyone else."  Your dad's response treated your statement as though you meant "only I should get my fair share."

(2/4) You sit down for dinner with your family. Everyone else gets a serving of the meal, and you don't get any.  You say, "I should get my fair share."  As a direct response, your dad corrects you, saying "***Everyone*** should get their fair share."

It was great to have so many talks highlighting the work done at @IULuddy and @IUBloomington. It was great hearing the speakers. And thanks to David Crandall, David Leake, and Roni Khardon for their effort in organizing this event! 30/30

Finally, Thomas Sterling concluding the day with "Domain-Specific Non-von Neumann HPC Architectures." Looking beyond our current architecture for solving real-time management of AI systems. 29/30 https://t.co/CXEhs9nrBv

Yijie Wang describing "Optimization Problems with $L_{0}$-norm." An extension of the Proximal Alternating Linearized Minimization (PALM) method with an application to Deep Neural Network Pruning (nodes and edges). 28/30 https://t.co/HZNdoJF3iO

Eleftherios Garyfallidis @garyfallidis overviewing "Stochastic Optimization / ML Theory." Fitting nonlinear models with noise and few samples, topology, QuickBundles, and simplicial homology for finding locally convex solutions. 27/30 https://t.co/MtDdiqgEKW

Ariful Azad with "Scalable Algorithms for Machine Learning on Graphs." Describing recent work in graph analytics, graph embeddings, and graph neural networks. Then overviewing high-performance-computing methods for solving graph problems. 26/30 https://t.co/ki3kuCrXGu

Qin Zhang on "Collaborative Learning with Limited Information." Solving best arm identification in m-Arm, K-Agent bandit problems, and the harder task of identifying top-m best arms. 25/n https://t.co/KUvHo7b1bM

Dirk Van Gucht "On the conditional independencies implication problem." The ongoing work for finding sound and complete reasoning systems for determining which conditional independencies are implied by a set of known CIs. 24/n https://t.co/RI9FjqW5mU

Xiaojing Liao & Xiaofeng Wang: "Intelligent Cybercrime Analysis." Creating credible cybersecurity knowledge networks for assessing crime, vulnerability, and misinformation. 23/n https://t.co/7LI0FdpbFl

Session 4: "Algorithms, Optimization, and Systems for AI"  Xiaofeng Wang & Haixu Tang: "Trustworthy Machine Learning." Discussing threat analysis in ML, the "passive misclassification attack" on audio, and the "active misclassification attack" with untrustworthy data 22/n https://t.co/hsAzI1QuQE

Paul Macklin @MathCancer discussing "Interfacing AI and non-AI techniques in Complex Applications." The overview included high performance computing for combining simulation and ML techniques, active learning during simulations, and applications toward precision health. 21/n https://t.co/wS9646f168

Filippo Meczer and Alessandro Flammini @OSoMe_IU on "AI Challenges in Countering Social Media Manipulation." Overviewing online bot detection, then methods for finding them based on the network structure, profile information, and temporal patterns. 20/n https://t.co/GmLYg2hJrM

Yuzhen Ye & Haixu Tang with "Full-Spectrum Prediction of Peptides Tandem Mass Spectra using Deep Neural Networks." Describing work on peptides sequences for breaking molecules and estimating likelihood. 19/n https://t.co/aangNtkc7E

YY Ahn @yy with "Learning useful representations of text, networks, and knowledge space." Leading with quantitative methods for evaluating clustering, semantic word changes between online communities, and ongoing projects with the ScientificGenome. 18/n https://t.co/HSSqmU5hgY

Memo Dalkilic @memodalkilic on "Data Analytics to Optimize Public Transportation on a College Campus." When a bus generates 300 GB of data in a month, high performance computing techniques and ML must optimize multiple criteria: maximizing goodwill as a solution. 17/n

Part 3: "Algorithms and Applications"  Starting with Raj Acharya on "Generalized Lattice Models" for metagenomics clustering to discern both the abundance and presence on DNA in natural settings. 16/n

Finally, David Crandall wrapped up the session with "Deep Learning and Probabilistic Models for 3D Scene Understanding." Challenges in matching data from multiple people and sources, online action detection, and 3D reasoning from the perspective of graphical models. 15/n https://t.co/Hu6TKJxgNk

David Leake describing "Leveraging Reasoning and Learning from Single Experiences." Case-based-Reasoning (CBR) as memory + analogy mapping + adaptation to fit new cases; then an overview of twin systems that pair black boxes with CBR systems trained on common data. 14/n https://t.co/kGxuaQj5Df

Michael Trossett with "Learning Submanifolds for Subsequent Inference on Random Dot Product Graphs." Mapping latent graph positions to low-dimensional manifolds, even when the manifold itself is unknown. 13/n https://t.co/n55IQEGMX1

Roni Khardon on "Learning Planning and Acting as Probabilistic Inference." Setting up the world as conditional random variables, then designing approximation criteria, general solutions for families of models, and theoretical analysis of the former. 12/n https://t.co/41iacpL4ma

Christopher Rafael describing "Exact Inference with Switching Kalman Filters," with an overview of the most likely path problem in graphical models, then an application to the best path through `n` music performances 11/n https://t.co/fX62BHqwES

Lantao Liu on "Informative Planning for Autonomous Robotics." Applications to environmental sensing and modeling through the lens of sparse Gaussian processes, and planning to navigate to maximize information gain. 10/n https://t.co/jwB9xMIzzF

Minje Kim discussing "Model and Feature Compression for Efficient Inference." Highlighted topics on efficiency in AI and learning latent representations from data; then discussing boosted hashing for bitwise source separation to gradually construct hash functions. 9/n https://t.co/jYvLV9DTIv

Session 2: "Machine Learning & Probabilistic Models"  Led by Donald Williamson's talk on "Using Machine Learning to Optimize Human Speech Perception in Noisy Environments." With applications to de-noising, and developing architectures, cost functions, and neuron models. 8/n https://t.co/KvSgPNB6xV
- David Cavar: "Knowledge Representations, Reasoning, and Natural Language" 7/n
